TOPIC: DOM MANIPULATION

WHAT IS DOM?

DOM stands for Document Object Model.

👉 It represents the HTML page as a tree structure that JavaScript can access and modify.

Real-life example:
👉 Think of a website like a tree 🌳

Root → HTML
Branches → tags
Leaves → content
WHY DOM IS USED?
To change content dynamically
To respond to user actions
To create interactive websites

Example:
👉 Clicking a button changes text
👉 Showing/hiding elements

DOM STRUCTURE (VISUAL)
HTML

│
├── head
│
└── body
    ├── h1
    ├── p
    └── button

👉 JavaScript can access any element in this tree

SELECTING ELEMENTS

getElementById()

let heading = document.getElementById("title");

getElementsByClassName()

let items = document.getElementsByClassName("item");

getElementsByTagName()

let divs = document.getElementsByTagName("div");

querySelector() (MOST USED)

let element = document.querySelector(".className");

querySelectorAll()

let elements = document.querySelectorAll("p");
CHANGING CONTENT

innerText

element.innerText = "Hello";

innerHTML

element.innerHTML = "<b>Hello</b>";

textContent

element.textContent = "Hello";
CHANGING STYLES
element.style.color = "red";
element.style.backgroundColor = "yellow";
ATTRIBUTES MANIPULATION

getAttribute()

element.getAttribute("id");

setAttribute()

element.setAttribute("class", "newClass");

removeAttribute()

element.removeAttribute("class");
ADDING & REMOVING ELEMENTS

createElement()

let newDiv = document.createElement("div");

append()

parent.append(newDiv);

prepend()

parent.prepend(newDiv);

remove()

element.remove();
EVENT HANDLING

👉 Events = user actions

Examples:

click
input
submit

addEventListener()

btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
  console.log("Button clicked");
});
REAL-LIFE EXAMPLE

BUTTON CLICK

HTML:

<button id="btn">Click Me</button>
<p id="text">Hello</p>

JS:

let btn = document.querySelector("#btn");
let text = document.querySelector("#text");

btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
  text.innerText = "Changed!";
});
VISUAL FLOW
User clicks button
        ↓
Event triggered
        ↓
JavaScript runs
        ↓
DOM updates
        ↓
Page changes
COMMON MISTAKES
Using wrong selectors
Forgetting # for id and . for class
Using innerHTML unnecessarily
Not waiting for DOM to load
